where $Y_{\text {exp }}, Y_{\text {pred }}$, and $\bar{Y}_{\text {training }}$ are the experimental activity, the predicted activity, and the mean experimental activity of the samples in the training set, respectively.

Value of $R^{2}$ varies directly with the increase in number of descriptors. Thus, $R^{2}$ is not reliable to measure the goodness of fit of the model. Therefore, $R^{2}$ is adjusted for the number of explanatory variables in the model. The adjusted $R^{2}$ is defined as

\[
R_{\text {adj }}^{2}=\frac{R^{2}-k(n-1)}{n-p+1},
\]

where $k$ is the number of independent variables in the model and $n$ is the number of descriptors.

The strength of the QSAR equation to predict bioactivity of a compound was determined using the leave-one-out cross-validation method. The revised formula for crossvalidation regression coefficient $\left(Q_{\mathrm{cv}}^{2}\right)$ is

\[
Q_{\mathrm{cv}}^{2}=1-\left[\frac{\sum\left(Y_{\text {pred }-Y_{\text {exp }}}\right)^{2}}{\sum\left(Y_{\text {exp }-\bar{Y}_{\text {training }}}\right)^{2}}\right],
\]

where $Y_{\text {pred }}, Y_{\text {exp }}$, and $\bar{Y}_{\text {training }}$ are the predicted, experimental, and mean values of experimental activity of the training set.

2.10. External Validation of Model. External validation of model was assessed by $R_{\text {test }}^{2}$ value. The closer the value of $R_{\text {test }}^{2}$ to $1.0$, the better the model generated.

